<subSubSection id="2ABD9BB59E093044F7CF2423259E4200" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" type="taxon discussion">
<paragraph id="D08FD80C4FA8FA5B556ED0A822E44C49" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">Taxon discussion</paragraph>
<paragraph id="F73C472447BAF267016831331E242165" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">
<taxonomicName id="52F2A045A5CD13F69905897510033BE3" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
(Figs 2, 3) was described from two male specimens collected in the 1960s from Krasnaya Polyana (Krasnodar Kray in Russian North Caucasus), but according to Papp &amp; Krivosheina (
<bibRefCitation id="5BDABFA674B4054FA13CBBC15064A8D9" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
) other material from the same collecting series had already been included in an overview by Mohrig et al. (
<bibRefCitation id="0EED7E8A689A869A92D8DA563F7709A2" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
: as 
<taxonomicName id="0AF2D38D93E661974358C2FC77333025" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="C625B94268261E2F248420BEFE793B2A" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023">
Using the key by Papp (
<bibRefCitation id="86D7EA60ED6DB59EA060A4FEE64C66E3" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Acta Zoologica Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="347 - 370" title="A study on Hesperinus Walker with description of a new species (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="56" year="2010">Papp 2010</bibRefCitation>
), the studied specimens run well to 
<taxonomicName id="E1ABC9EB2B9708461C8C2669CB276C0A" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
because of the elongated terminal flagellomere (Fig. 2c), wing length about 6 mm (Fig. 2b), considerably shorter and broader first flagellomere with specific setation (Fig. 2d), and gonostylus mediodorsally with a projecting lobe (Fig. 3c). Like the European 
<taxonomicName id="AD20A6D61DA3E48DFF3721F7AE981817" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
, the females of 
<taxonomicName id="D9C8BFDBC334A4FC5356A3F454ABA04F" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus ninae" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ninae">Hesperinus ninae</taxonomicName>
are flightless. In spite, that there were no females included to the original description (
<bibRefCitation id="E6284B7A426878C8A3C7B54BC4D157C4" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
), four of them from the same collecting series were studied by Mohrig et al. (
<bibRefCitation id="7358F6F3B31625DBB23BC602E0C355D3" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
, as 
<taxonomicName id="6583BD2FEAB8160E2B27386517766848" class="Insecta" family="Hesperinidae" genus="Hesperinus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Hesperinus imbecillus" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="imbecillus">Hesperinus imbecillus</taxonomicName>
). They figured a female with reduced wings (
<bibRefCitation id="9CEB3F6E4AF9357D16F8D695F8BE096B" author="Mohrig, W." journalOrPublisher="Zoologischer Anzeiger" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="339 - 344" title="Zur Kenntnis fluegelreduzierter Dipteren der Bodenstreu. VII. Beitrag. Gattung Hesperinus (Diptera, Hesperinidae)" volume="194" year="1975">Mohrig et al. 1975</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1) and did not described any differences between Northern Caucasian and Central European material (see also discussion by 
<bibRefCitation id="0BB95F4FF651BE802BDD03A26C700125" author="Papp, L." journalOrPublisher="Russian Entomological Journal" pageId="0" pageNumber="1023" pagination="293 - 297" title="Description of a new species of Hesperinus Walker, 1848 from the North Caucasus (Diptera: Hesperinidae)" volume="18" year="2010">Papp and Krivosheina 2010</bibRefCitation>
). The flightlessness has obviously been an adaptive response to unfavourable climatic conditions and has set further limits to dispersal. However, the current record is at quite a remote distance from the type locality, indicating that the species probably has a wide distribution in suitable habitats in the Caucasus.
</paragraph>
